 Martyr, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place called Bland in Sedburgh, Yorkshire, the origin of which is uncertain. Possibly it is from Old English <i>(ge)bland</i> ‘storm, commotion’ (from <i>blandan</i> ‘to blend or mingle’), with reference to its exposed situation. The modern English adjective <i>bland</i> did not come into English (from Latin) until the 15th century, and is therefore unlikely to have given rise to surnames.","French: nickname from Old French <i>blant</i> ‘flattering’ (from Latin <i>blandus</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Blandin","meanings":["French: derivative of   Bland  .","Altered form of   Blanding  , a surname of English origin."]},{"name":"Blend","meanings":["Possibly English: variant of   Bland  .","German: unexplained."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Annia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["pet form of   Anna  , apparently derived from the Low German name <i>Anniken</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Annia Bland was born in 1476, in London, England. She had at least 3 sons with John William Atkins. She died in 1530, in Surrey, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1476–1530":"1476–1530","1475–1540":"1475–1540","1500–1540":"1500–1540","1504–1540":"1504–1540","1515–1540":"1515–1540","1500":"1500","1476":"1476","1530":"1530","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","29 October 1504":"29. oktoober 1504","1515":"1515","1504":"1504","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Gregory, London, England":"London, England","City of London, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"City of London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St George The Martyr, Surrey, England":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1476–1530":"1476–1530","1475–1540":"1475–1540","1500–1540":"1500–1540","1504–1540":"1504–1540","1515–1540":"1515–1540","1500":"1500","1476":"1476","1530":"1530","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","29 October 1504":"29. lokakuuta 1504","1515":"1515","1504":"1504","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","St Gregory, London, Engla